</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="9FBC05D4FF9FFF99C76CFAA4DC67FA9A" authority="Hayek" authorityName="Hayek" box="[597,775,1284,1309]" class="Eudicots" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Cardaminopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="7" pageNumber="50" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6AC8A245FF9FFF99C76CFAA4DC67FA9A" box="[597,775,1284,1309]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="50">Cardaminopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) used by this species for larval development, suggested that Cantabrian populations could represent a new taxon different from the widespread European 
<taxonomicName id="9FBC05D4FF9FFF99C725FAF4DDA5FAEA" box="[540,709,1364,1389]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Meligethes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subaeneus">
<emphasis id="6AC8A245FF9FFF99C725FAF4DDA5FAEA" box="[540,709,1364,1389]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="50">M. subaeneus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, no evidence of strong morphological differentiation was observed among the 
<taxonomicName id="9FBC05D4FF9FFF99C61FFADCDCC9FA12" box="[806,937,1404,1429]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Cardamine" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="7" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6AC8A245FF9FFF99C61FFADCDCC9FA12" box="[806,937,1404,1429]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="50">Cardamine</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
­ or 
<emphasis id="6AC8A245FF9FFF99C6CFFADCDBD2FA12" box="[1014,1202,1404,1429]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="50">Cardaminopsis­</emphasis>
associated European populations, albeit the specimens of 
<emphasis id="6AC8A245FF9FFF99C667FA04DB7AFA3A" box="[862,1050,1444,1469]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="50">Cardaminopsis­</emphasis>
associated populations exhibit a relatively smaller and narrower pronotum (ratio WPR 
<number id="EE746C70FF9FFF99C127FA6CDB47FA61" box="[1054,1063,1484,1510]" pageId="7" pageNumber="50" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<collectionCode id="3EADE692FF9FFF99C109FA6CDBE6FA61" box="[1072,1158,1484,1510]" pageId="7" pageNumber="50">WELY</collectionCode>
[
<figureCitation id="C08762D2FF9FFF99C1A3FA6CDB97FA61" box="[1178,1271,1484,1510]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="10.[264,368,1773,1797]" captionTargetBox="[290,1257,324,1772]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[264,1323,298,1790]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 17. Schematic drawings of morphological characters measurements for Meligethes species—a: body shape and pronotum; b: antennae; c: protibiae; d: protarsi; e: tegmen; f: aedeagus; g: aedeagal apex. Refer to Table 2 for list of characters and acronyms." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173306/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="50">
Fig. 
<number id="EE746C70FF9FFF99C1E0FA6CDB97FA61" box="[1241,1271,1484,1510]" pageId="7" pageNumber="50" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
a] = 
<number id="EE746C70FF9FFF99C431FA54DE1FF989" box="[264,383,1524,1550]" pageId="7" pageNumber="50" value="0.875" valueMax="0.9" valueMin="0.85">0.85–0.90</number>
) in comparison with specimens of 
<emphasis id="6AC8A245FF9FFF99C678FA54DCADF98A" box="[833,973,1524,1549]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="50">Cardamine­</emphasis>
associated populations (ratio WPR 
<number id="EE746C70FF9FFF99C470F9BCDE31F9B1" box="[329,337,1564,1590]" pageId="7" pageNumber="50" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<collectionCode id="3EADE692FF9FFF99C462F9BCDED1F9B1" box="[347,433,1564,1590]" pageId="7" pageNumber="50">WELY</collectionCode>
[
<figureCitation id="C08762D2FF9FFF99C4F0F9BCDD49F9B1" box="[457,553,1564,1590]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="10.[264,368,1773,1797]" captionTargetBox="[290,1257,324,1772]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[264,1323,298,1790]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 17. Schematic drawings of morphological characters measurements for Meligethes species—a: body shape and pronotum; b: antennae; c: protibiae; d: protarsi; e: tegmen; f: aedeagus; g: aedeagal apex. Refer to Table 2 for list of characters and acronyms." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173306/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="50">
